  "prompt_text": "You are a newly appointed plant manager at a large automotive assembly plant in Southeastern Michigan.  You are responsible for all activities that occur at your facility.  This includes, but is not limited to, profit and loss, projects, quality, employment levels, safety, meeting production demands, and more.  You oversee a 10-person executive staff, including an environmental director, occupational safety and health director, engineering director, maintenance director, finance director, assembly director, Body-In-White (BIW) director, paint shop director, human relations (HR) director, Logistics/shipping director, and executive secretary.  The assembly plant produces vehicles that are both sold in the United States and exported globally.  As a result of overall demand, the facility employs approximately 8,300 direct employees, 2,000 contract employees, and operates 24 hours a day across three shifts, six to seven days a week. At any given time, up to 6,000 assembled vehicles may be stored onsite awaiting delivery, depending on available space. The plant ships approximately 1,200 finished vehicles to dealerships and other distribution networks daily. The overall site footprint includes five major buildings: an administrative building, paint shop, assembly building, BIW building, and utilities building, as well as several ancillary buildings for miscellaneous operations.\r\n\tRecently, the facility has received significant capital to upgrade its infrastructure.  The first thing updated was the personal industrial vehicle (PIV) program.  This includes equipment such as forklift trucks, personal mobility vehicles, and other small individual mobile equipment that were powered by 2,000+ pound (lb) lead-acid batteries, as well as 80 waste vehicle lithium-phosphate batteries.  The plant upgraded to a hydrogen fuel cell-based PIV equipment program.  This allows mobile equipment to refill in 4 minutes as opposed to charging lead-acid batteries for 12 hours.  Since PIV equipment can now recharge in 4 minutes, as opposed to 12 hours, fewer PIV equipment units are required on-site due to virtually zero equipment downtime required for charging.  With the program, a large 8,500 lb hydrogen storage tank system and distribution network were installed directly outside the plant.  Over eight hundred 2,000+ lb batteries were stored awaiting recycling in one of the ancillary buildings near the hydrogen fuel system and oil/fuel storage area.\r\n\tEach finished vehicle receives eight gallons of fuel prior to shipping off-site, resulting in a daily average fuel consumption of 9,600 gallons.  As a result, fuel trucks are constantly supplying the 20,000-gallon above-ground storage tank (AST).  \r\n\tAt 12:34 pm EST on April 14, 2026, a fuel truck carrying a full load (approximately 8,000 gallons) of gasoline for delivery to the 20,000-gallon AST committed a terrorist attack.  The fuel truck driver drove as fast as possible through the plant and intentionally rammed the 8,500 lb hydrogen fuel tank, causing a massive explosion.  This explosion caused a chain reaction, igniting the fuel in the truck, the remaining fuel in the gasoline AST, as well as the oil stored in the oil/fuel storage area nearby.  The explosion decimated everything within a 600-foot (ft) radius, including part of the Assembly building, battery storage area, and part of the paint shop.  Many fatalities and significant injuries have occurred. Fires are raging, especially at the battery storage area, and operations have immediately ceased throughout the plant. Oil from the tank farm is now flowing to storm sewers and has made its way to international navigable waterways. The full initial extent of the damage is unknown.  Personnel in the plant are panicking and trying to leave as expeditiously as possible.  \r\n\tPlease reference the attached files IncidentSeverityClassificationFramework.docx, AssemblyPlantStaffingLevels.xlsx, AdditionalContext.docx, and FacilityBuildingLayout.xlsx for grading information, facility staffing information, and important background information.  The severity classification scale is defined in the IncidentSeverityClassificationFramework.docx file. The facility operates under a structured emergency response framework aligned with standard Incident Command System (ICS) principles and corporate emergency response procedures. As the plant manager and highest-ranking incident commander on-site, you are responsible for taking control of the situation and establishing an incident command location. You must decide how to handle the situation. Your priority hierarchy is personnel safety, environment, and process/infrastructure. In a 5–8-page document titled TerroristActIncidentBreakdown.docx, detail the decisions you make in the first five minutes, the decisions made in minutes five through 15, and the decisions made after 15 minutes within the first hour. At the transition between each time phase (0–5 minutes, 5–15 minutes, and 15–60 minutes), include a decision-gate checkpoint where new information is reassessed and subsequent actions are adjusted accordingly. Detail both what the decision was and why the decision was made.  Topics in TerroristActIncidentBreakdown.docx should include, but not be limited to, emergency responders' access, communication, and methods, setup and administering medical services, safe evacuation, business continuity, environmental concerns, communication strategy, and public-facing communication approach (including how messaging is managed, who is responsible, and when communication occurs, but not requiring drafted communication content), logistics, facilities management, and incident documentation. Information in the TerroristActIncidentBreakdown.docx file should include a site incident severity assessment for each media (health/safety, environmental, public relations, HR, etc.), identify stakeholders and define notification order, timing, and method, and distribution of resources. Classify severity using a defined scale (e.g., Low/Moderate/High/Critical) for each category.",
