      "content": "Each building in the complex has an audible emergency evacuation alarm and speaker system.  \nThe Human Relations (HR) has an employee and contractor badge access system as well as cell phone numbers for all employees/contractors.\nThe Leadership team is the same as the incident commander team.  \nThe incident command center is located in the administration building in the conference room next to the plant manager’s office. \n All 3 main roadways around the plant are always heavily congested. Even during non-rush hour times.  The facility, due to its location, sometimes experiences traffic bottlenecks, which prevent anyone from coming on-site or leaving. \nPolice officers often patrol the area during shift change to ensure no one creates chaos while leaving due to pedestrian traffic and can assist in traffic flow if needed.  \nThe HR director works very closely with the police chief regarding plant traffic for any unusual events.  \nWhen emergency preparedness table-top exercises are conducted, it is the Occupational Health and Safety leadership who meets and guides emergency services at the plant truck entrances.  \nEvery turnstile entrance frairom the parking lots has a digital badge reader\nThe Environmental Department has several personnel and resources for spill clean-up.\nGeneral employee training allows employees to take defensive spill clean-up/spill migration measures only if it is safe to do so.\nWhen Environmental spills are too large to clean up by on-site staff, professional external resources are contacted to come and clean up the spill.  The companies contacted specialize in cleaning up large industrial spills.\nSeveral Federal, State, and local agencies are required to be called in the event of a spill.  The agency called depends on the scope of the spill.  \nThe assembly plant operates on a Just-in-Time (JIT) logistically complicated supply chain, a heavily dependent business model that includes trucking and rail transport.  \nThe plant unloads 200-300 fully loaded semi-tractor-trailer trucks daily and dozens of rail cars.\nThe company has a corporate media relations director who handles all public-facing communications. \nDuring an evacuation order, it is the engineering director’s responsibility to work with the facilities department to shut off all operations as quickly as possible with the help of hourly trades who will stay behind to complete this activity.   \nBuilding closure policies require a final sweep of each affected building after evacuation by leadership.\nDuring true emergency events, cost must not be a concern.  The finance team works with the corporate team to issue whatever purchase orders are required to ensure there are no delays in emergency services. \nThe business continuity oversees all operations throughout North America. The logistics department handles immediate issues, while the business continuity team handles regional issues.  \nThe plant’s Leadership Team functions as the on-site Incident Command Team (ICT).  While formal ICS documentation and procedures exist at the corporate level, plant-level response is guided by these established principles, including unified command, span of control, and clear role delegation. \nUpon arrival of external emergency responders, incident command is transferred in accordance with ICS protocols, and plant leadership transitions into a support role."
