      "content": "Incident Severity Classification Framework\nPurpose\nThis document defines the standard severity classification scale and associated numerical scoring to be used for all incident assessments across operational, safety, environmental, and business functions. The goal is to ensure consistent evaluation, communication, and prioritization of response actions taken. This framework should be used during initial incident triage and reassessed as additional information becomes available.\nSeverity Classification Scale and Scoring\nLow (Score: 1)\nMinimal impact to operations or personnel\nNo injuries or only minor first-aid cases\nNo environmental release or negligible impact\nNo external reporting required (Environmental Protection Agency, National Response Center, Michigan Department of Energy, Great Lakes, and Environment)\nEasily contained by on-site personnel\nModerate (Score: 2)\nLocalized operational disruption\nMinor injuries requiring medical attention (non-life-threatening)\nContained environmental release with limited impact\nManageable with site-level resources\nHigh (Score: 3)\nSignificant operational disruption or partial shutdown\nSerious injuries or multiple medical cases\nEnvironmental release with measurable off-site impact risk\nRegulatory reporting required\nRequires external support (emergency responders, specialists)\nCritical (Score: 4)\nCatastrophic event with widespread impact\nFatalities or life-threatening injuries\nMajor environmental release affecting surrounding areas or waterways\nImmediate regulatory and public notification required\nFull site shutdown and multi-agency emergency response\nScoring Application\nEach incident should be scored independently across key categories such as:\n- Health & Safety\n- Environmental Impact\n- Business Continuity / Logistics\n- Operational / Production Impact\n- Public Relations / Reputation\n- Human Resources / Workforce Impact\n\nAssign a score from 1 to 4 for each category based on the definitions above.\nOverall Severity Determination\nThe overall incident severity should be determined using the highest individual category score.\nExample: If Safety = 4 (Critical) and Environmental = 2 (Moderate), the overall severity is Critical.\nApplication Guidance\n- Assess severity independently for each category.\n- Default to the higher severity level when uncertain.\n- Reassess severity as conditions evolve."
