thorities\n- Employee communication separate from media communication\n\n---\n\n## Decision 17: Activate Business Continuity and Supply Chain Interruption Protocols\n**Decision:** Notify business continuity and suspend inbound JIT logistics to prevent cascading regional disruption.\n\n**Why:** The plant unloads hundreds of trucks daily and relies on JIT flow. If not stopped quickly, congestion and inventory misrouting will worsen.\n\n### Actions\n- Halt inbound parts deliveries\n- Divert or hold rail shipments\n- Stop finished vehicle shipping\n- Preserve inventory and shipping records\n- Coordinate with North America business continuity team for rerouting and customer impact planning\n\n---\n\n## Decision Gate Checkpoint: End of 5–15 Minutes\n\n### New Information Likely Available\n- First responders are on scene or arriving\n- Fire behavior and battery fire conditions are clearer\n- Missing persons numbers are emerging\n- Perimeter and traffic control improving but still stressed\n- Environmental release confirmed off-site\n- Need for specialized hazmat, foam, heavy rescue, and spill contractors confirmed\n\n### Reassessment\nThe incident remains **Critical** in all categories. The key transition now is from plant-led emergency stabilization to **external-agency-led tactical response with plant support**. Decision-making must adjust to unified command, sustained medical operations, family support, and long-duration outage management.\n\n---\n\n# Phase III: 15–60 Minutes\n\n## Primary Objectives for 15–60 Minutes\n- Transfer or unify command with public responders\n- Support rescue/fire suppression/hazmat operations\n- Improve accountability and family support\n- Formalize environmental response\n- Stabilize perimeter, traffic, and communications\n- Start continuity and recovery planning without interfering with rescue/investigation\n\n---\n\n## Decision 18: Transfer/Integrate Command Under ICS Protocols\n**Decision:** Upon arrival of appropriate public emergency a