ructed where to report status and where not to return\n\n---\n\n## Decision 24: Resource Distribution and Emergency Procurement\n**Decision:** Finance authorizes immediate emergency purchase orders and vendor commitments with no delay for cost concerns.\n\n**Why:** The context explicitly states cost must not be a concern during true emergency events.\n\n### Resources to prioritize\n- Firefighting foam / hazmat support\n- Spill response contractors and materials\n- Barricades, lighting, generators, radios\n- Water/food/restroom support for evacuees and responders\n- Counseling and family assistance services\n- Temporary command and communications equipment\n- Security augmentation\n\n---\n\n## Decision 25: Facility Stabilization and Adjacent Building Protection\n**Decision:** Under unified command, support protection of undamaged/less-damaged areas and confirm isolation of threatened utilities and process systems.\n\n**Why:** Preventing escalation protects life, property, and future recovery potential.\n\n### Focus areas\n- Paint shop hazards\n- Utility building interdependencies\n- Remaining fuel sources\n- Compressed gas systems\n- Electrical isolation\n- Structural assessment of Assembly/Paint/adjacent buildings\n- Protection of stored finished vehicles if they create additional fire load or access blockage\n\n---\n\n## Decision 26: Initial Recovery and Continuity Planning Begins—But Only in Parallel\n**Decision:** Begin planning for continuity and recovery in parallel, without diverting resources from rescue, firefighting, and stabilization.\n\n**Why:** The outage will likely be prolonged and regionally disruptive. Early planning reduces downstream chaos.\n\n### Continuity planning topics\n- Alternate production allocation within North America\n- Supplier communications and shipment holds\n- Customer/dealer/export impact\n- Payroll continuity for workforce\n- Contractor management\n- Site closure duration scenarios\n- Security of finished vehicles and inventory\n