ions.\n\n#### **Decision-Gate Checkpoint 1 (Minute 5)**\n*   *Information Reassessment:* Are the alarms functioning? Is the Administration building secure from the advancing chemical fires? Have external authorities acknowledged the dispatch?\n*   *Adjustment:* If the wind pushes toxic lithium/lead-acid smoke toward the Admin building, the ICC will immediately relocate to an off-site or upwind ancillary building. If the PA system is compromised by the blast, area Directors will use megaphones and physical sweeps to direct the evacuation.\n\n---\n\n### 4. PHASE 2: 5–15 MINUTES (COMMAND SETUP, ACCESS, & CONTAINMENT)\n**Primary Priorities:** Triage setup, environmental mitigation, and securing business continuity channels.\n\n**Decision 2.1: Establish Medical Triage and Staging Areas**\n*   *Decision:* OHS Director, working with the first arriving EMS units, will establish a casualty collection point and triage center in a secure parking lot near the turnstiles, well outside the hot zone.\n*   *Rationale:* The high number of severe injuries requires immediate triage. Moving the wounded to a designated cold zone protects them from secondary battery/oil explosions.\n\n**Decision 2.2: Defensive Environmental Containment & External Escalation**\n*   *Decision:* Direct the Environmental Director to deploy trained staff to take *defensive* spill clean-up measures (e.g., placing booms around unaffected storm drains) *only* if safe. Simultaneously, direct the Finance Director to issue an emergency PO to dispatch our contracted external large-industrial spill response firm.\n*   *Rationale:* Oil is actively flowing into international navigable waterways. General employees are only trained for defensive measures. Because this is a massive hazardous release, specialized external contractors must be mobilized immediately. Cost is zero object.\n\n**Decision 2.3: Halt Logistics and JIT Supply Chain**\n*   *Decision:* Direct the Logistics Director to contact all trucking companies and rail operators to immediately halt inbound shipments and reroute current transit to regional holding lots.\n*   *Rationale:* The plant unloads 200-300 trucks daily. Allowing them to arrive will fatally choke the roadways needed by emergency responders and mass-casualty transport. \n\n**Decision 2.4: Personnel Accountability Communication**\n*   *Decision:* Direct the HR Director to utilize the cell phone notification system to send a mass text to all 10,300+ direct and contract employees. The message will instruct them to remain at safe muster points, not to enter vehicles (which causes traffic), and to check in.\n*   *Rationale:* We must establish who is missing in the blast zone. Stopping employees from driving away keeps the roads clear for emergency vehicles. \n\n**Decision 2.5: Notify Corporate Public Relations & Business Continuity**\n*   *Decision:* Contact the Corporate Media Relations Director and the North American Business Continuity Team.\n*   *Rationale:* A terrorist attack will immediately leak to social media and news outlets. Corporate PR must control the external narrative. Business Continuity must begin assessing the regional supply chain impact of losing this facility.\n\n#### **Decision-Gate Checkpoint 2 (Minute 15)**\n*   *Information Reassessment:* Have the Fire Department and local law enforcement assumed tactical command? Is the environmental contractor en route? \n*   *Adjustment:* In accordance with ICS protocols, I will formally transfer tactical Incident Command to the highest-ranking external Fire/Emergency Chief upon their arrival. The plant ICT will transition into a Unified Command support role. If oil continues bypassing defensive booms, we will prepare to notify international waterway authorities (Coast Guard) immediately.\n\n---\n\n### 5. PHASE 3: 15–60 MINUTES (STABILIZATION, ACCOUNTABILITY, & COMPLIANCE)\n**Primary Priorities:** Personnel accountability, regulatory compliance, and incident documentation.\n\n**Decision 3.1: Reconcile Personnel Accountability (Roll Call)**\n*   *Decision:* HR will run a digital report from the turnstile badge readers to determine exactly who was on-site at 12:34 PM. This list will be cross-referenced with the mass-text responses and physical muster point counts.\n*   *Rationale:* First responders need an accurate manifest of missing persons to conduct targeted search and rescue in the rubble of the Assembly and Paint buildings. \n\n**Decision 3.2: Final Building Sweeps**\n*   *Decision:* Direct the Assembly, BIW, and Paint Directors to coordinate with Fire Department Rescue teams to conduct final sweeps of the *unaffected* buildings (Admin, Utilities, BIW).\n*   *Rationale:* Compliance with corporate building closure policy. This ensures no personnel are left behind due to injury or failure to hear the alarms, without putting plant leadership in the active fire zones.\n\n**Decision 3.3: Regulatory Notifications**\n*   *Decision:* The Environmental Director will begin executing mandatory calls to the EPA, National Response Center (NRC), and state environmental agencies (EGLE). \n*   *Rationale:* Federal and international law requires immediate reporting of significant oil/chemical discharges into navigable waterways. Delays in reporting carry severe legal and financial penalties.\n\n**Decision 3.4: Secure Completed Inventory**\n*   *Decision:* Direct Logistics to ensure the 6,000 finished vehicles stored on-site are secure and that fuel trucks on-site are isolated and powered down.\n*   *Rationale:* The finished vehicles contain up to 48,000 gallons of gasoline. They must be protected from spreading fires to prevent further catastrophic chain reactions.\n\n**Decision 3.5: Incident Documentation and Scribe Verification**\n*   *Decision:* Review the Executive Secretary’s documentation log of all decisions, times, and dispatches.\n*   *Rationale:* Meticulous documentation is a core ICS principle. This log will be crucial for the FBI, Homeland Security, EPA, and