        "response": "# TerroristActIncidentBreakdown.docx\n\n# Terrorist Act Incident Breakdown\n## Assembly Plant Hydrogen Tank Attack — April 14, 2026, 12:34 PM EST\n\n---\n\n## Site Incident Severity Assessment\n\nThe following severity classifications are assigned based on the Incident Severity Classification Framework. These are initial assessments made upon recognition of the event and are subject to reassessment at each decision-gate checkpoint.\n\n| Category | Severity | Score | Justification |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Health & Safety | **Critical** | 4 | Mass-casualty event with confirmed fatalities and significant injuries across multiple buildings; 600-ft blast radius during peak operations with thousands of personnel on-site |\n| Environmental Impact | **Critical** | 4 | Oil flowing to storm sewers and reaching international navigable waterways; lithium-phosphate battery fires producing toxic fumes; gasoline and hydrogen combustion releasing hazardous emissions; multi-media contamination (air, water, soil) |\n| Business Continuity / Logistics | **Critical** | 4 | All operations ceased; JIT supply chain disrupted; 200–300 daily truck deliveries and rail shipments halted; up to 6,000 stored vehicles potentially at risk; complete site shutdown |\n| Operational / Production Impact | **Critical** | 4 | Assembly building partially destroyed; paint shop partially destroyed; battery storage area decimated; hydrogen fuel system destroyed; gasoline AST destroyed; infrastructure loss is catastrophic |\n| Public Relations / Reputation | **Critical** | 4 | Terrorist attack on a major automotive facility; mass casualties; environmental contamination of international waterways; immediate and sustained national/international media attention |\n| Human Resources / Workforce Impact | **Critical** | 4 | Fatalities and serious injuries among approximately 10,300 personnel (direct + contract employees); psychological trauma across entire workforce; shift operations across 24/7 schedule affected |\n\n**Overall Incident Severity: CRITICAL (Score: 4)**\n\nThis is the highest-severity classification across every assessment category. The incident involves mass casualties, catastrophic infrastructure destruction, major environmental contamination of international waterways, a confirmed terrorist act, and complete operational shutdown.\n\n---\n\n## Stakeholder Identification, Notification Order, Timing, and Method\n\nThe following notification sequence is prioritized by immediacy of need, legal obligation, and operational dependency. Notifications are initiated as soon as practically possible within each time phase, with the understanding that life-safety actions take absolute priority over communications in the first minutes.\n\n| Priority | Stakeholder | Notification Timing | Method | Responsible Party |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | 911 / Emergency Services (Fire, EMS, Police, HazMat) | Immediate (0–2 min) | Phone (911 call) | Plant Manager or designee / Security |\n| 2 | On-site Leadership / Incident Command Team | Immediate (0–3 min) | Direct communication / radio / phone | Plant Manager |\n| 3 | All On-site Personnel (employees & contractors) | Immediate (0–3 min) | Building evacuation alarms and PA speaker systems | Plant Manager directive; executed by building leadership |\n| 4 | FBI / Department of Homeland Security (DHS) | Within 5–10 min | Phone (FBI field office and DHS hotline) | Plant Manager / Security |\n| 5 | Corporate Emergency Management / Executive Leadership | Within 5–15 min | Phone call followed by email | Plant Manager |\n| 6 | Corporate Media Relations Director | Within 5–15 min | Phone call | Plant Manager / Executive Secretary |\n| 7 | National Response Center (NRC) | Within 15 min | Phone (NRC hotline: 1-800-424-8802) | Environmental Director |\n| 8 | EPA Region 5 | Within 15–30 min | Phone | Environmental Director |\n| 9 | Michigan Dept. of Energy, Great Lakes, and Environment (EGLE) | Within 15–30 min | Phone | Environmental Director |\n| 10 | Local Police Chief (traffic and perimeter coordination) | Within 5–15 min | Phone | HR Director |\n| 11 | OSHA (Area Office) | Within 8 hours (per regulatory requirement, but initial contact within first hour) | Phone | Occupational Safety and Health Director |\n| 12 | External Environmental Spill Cleanup Contractors | Within 15–30 min | Phone / Emergency dispatch | Environmental Director |\n| 13 | Business Continuity Team (Corporate/North America) | Within 15–30 min | Phone and email | Logistics/Shipping Director |\n| 14 | Insurance Carrier / Risk Management | Within 30–60 min | Phone | Finance Director |\n| 15 | Employee Families (mass notification) | Within 60 min (after headcount and casualty identification processes are underway) | HR mass text/phone system; company hotline | HR Director |\n| 16 | Supply Chain Partners / Dealers | Within 1–4 hours | Phone and email | Logistics/Shipping Director / Business Continuity |\n| 17 | Local Elected Officials / Community Leaders | Within 1–4 hours | Phone | Corporate Communications |\n| 18 | Union Leadership (if applicable) | Within 30–60 min | Phone | HR Director |\n\n---\n\n## Phase 1: First Five Minutes (12:34 PM – 12:39 PM)\n\n### Situational Awareness\n\nAt 12:34 PM, a catastrophic explosion occurs. The plant manager, located in the administration building, hears and feels the blast. Initial information is fragmentary: a massive fireball is visible, buildings are damaged, and personnel are in panic. The full scope is unknown, but the scale of the explosion—felt across the entire facility—immediately signals a worst-case scenario.\n\n### Decision 1: Activate Full-Site Emergency Evacuation\n\n**Decision:** Order immediate activation of all building emergency evacuation alarms and PA systems across all five major buildings and all ancillary buildings, directing all personnel to evacuate to designated assembly points away from the blast zone and away from the direction of visible fire and smoke.\n\n**Why:** Personnel safety is the absolute first priority. With approximately 3,400–3,500 employees on the current shift (plus contract workers), and with fires raging, secondary explosions possible from the battery storage area and remaining fuel, and unknown structural integrity of partially destroyed buildings, every second of delay increases the casualty count. The building alarm and speaker systems are the fastest method to reach all personnel simultaneously. Evacuation must be directed away from the south/southeast area of the site where the explosion, hydrogen tank, AST, battery storage, and oil storage are located.\n\n### Decision 2: Call 911\n\n**Decision:** Direct the executive secretary or any available staff member to immediately call 911, reporting a major explosion at the facility with mass casualties, active fires including chemical/battery fires, fuel and oil spills, and confirming this is believed to be an intentional attack. Request fire, EMS, HazMat, and law enforcement response at maximum capacity.\n\n**Why:** The scale of this event far exceeds on-site response capability. Multiple fire types are burning simultaneously (gasoline, oil, hydrogen, lithium-phosphate batteries), there are mass casualties requiring emergency medical transport, and the site is a potential active crime scene. Early activation of mutual aid ensures the fastest possible arrival of resources. Communicating the suspected terrorist nature immediately allows law enforcement to begin securing the area and activating federal response protocols.\n\n### Decision 3: Assemble Incident Command Team\n\n**Decision:** Direct all available members of the 10-person leadership team to immediately report to the incident command center (administration building conference room), or if the administration building is compromised, to a pre-designated alternate location upwind and away from the blast zone.\n\n**Why:** Unified command is essential for coordinated response. Each director has specific emergency responsibilities that must be activated simultaneously. The ICS structure requires a functioning command post with clear role delegation. The administration building is one of the five major buildings and its status relative to the 600-foot blast radius must be confirmed. If it is within the affected zone or downwind of toxic smoke, an alternate command post must be established immediately. Based on the facility layout, the administration building appears to be situated away from the explosion area, making it the likely viable command location.\n\n### Decision 4: Direct Engineering Director to Initiate Emergency Shutdown Procedures\n\n**Decision:** Contact the Engineering Director and direct immediate emergency shutdown of all plant operations, utilities, and gas lines, with support from hourly trades personnel who will remain behind specifically for this purpose per established protocol.\n\n**Why:** Per established plant procedures, the Engineering Director is responsible for working with facilities to shut off all operations during an evacuation order. With active fires near the fuel storage area, oil tank farm, and battery storage, shutting down gas lines, electrical feeds to damaged areas, and other utilities prevents additional fuel sources from feeding fires and reduces secondary explosion risk. Trades personnel trained for this function execute these shutdowns while other employees evacuate.\n\n### Decision 5: Direct Occupational Safety and Health Director to Prepare to Meet and Guide Emergency Responders\n\n**Decision:** Direct the Occupational Safety and Health Director (and available OSH staff) to proceed to the plant truck entrances to meet, guide, and brief arriving emergency services on the nature of the hazards, site layout, and known casualty locations.\n\n**Why:** Per established emergency preparedness protocols, OSH leadership meets and guides emergency services at truck entrances during emergencies. Arriving fire, EMS, and HazMat units will be unfamiliar with the specific layout of this 5-building complex, the location of the hydrogen system, battery storage hazards (lithium-phosphate fires require specialized suppression), and the oil/fuel storage areas. Providing immediate on-site guidance prevents responder delays and ensures they do not inadvertently enter the most dangerous zones without proper preparation.\n\n### Decision 6: Direct HR Director to Contact Local Police for Traffic and Perimeter Control\n\n**Decision:** Direct the HR Director to immediately contact the local police chief to request emergency traffic control on all three major roadways surrounding the plant, establishing perimeter security and creating clear emergency vehicle access corridors.\n\n**Why:** All three roadways around the plant are always heavily congested. With thousands of panicking employees attempting to evacuate by vehicle simultaneously, and emergency vehicles needing to arrive, a traffic gridlock will develop within minutes that could prevent ambulances and fire trucks from reaching the site. The HR Director has an established working relationship with the police chief specifically for traffic management during unusual events. Police officers who often patrol during shift changes can be immediately redeployed. Establishing emergency vehicle corridors is life-critical: delayed ambulance access directly translates to preventable deaths.\n\n---\n\n## Decision-Gate Checkpoint 1 (12:39 PM — Transition from Phase 1 to Phase 2)\n\n### Information Reassessment:\n\nAt the five-minute mark, the following information is being gathered and assessed:\n\n- **Evacuation status:** Alarms are sounding in all buildings. Personnel are streaming out of exits, though congestion is occurring at turnstile exits from parking lots. Reports from building leadership are beginning to arrive regarding areas where personnel cannot evacuate (structural collapse in parts of the Assembly building and Paint Shop).\n- **Fire status:** Multiple fires are burning intensely. The battery storage area fire is producing thick, toxic smoke (lithium-phosphate battery fires release hydrofluoric acid, phosphorus pentoxide, and other toxic gases). The gasoline AST fire and oil tank farm fire are producing massive heat and smoke columns.\n- **Casualty reports:** Initial reports indicate multiple fatalities in the immediate blast zone and dozens of injuries ranging from blast trauma, burns, and smoke inhalation. Personnel in the destroyed portions of the Assembly building and near the battery storage area are unaccounted for.\n- **Infrastructure status:** Part of the Assembly building is destroyed. Part of the Paint Shop is destroyed. The battery storage ancillary building is decimated. The hydrogen system, fuel truck, and AST are completely destroyed. Oil from the tank farm is confirmed flowing to storm sewers.\n- **Command post status:** The administration building is intact and accessible. The incident command center is being activated.\n- **External response:** 911 has been called. Police are beginning to respond to traffic control requests. Fire and EMS units are en route but have not yet arrived due to traffic congestion.\n- **Security concern:** The terrorist nature of the attack means there could be secondary threats (additional attackers, secondary devices). This must be communicated to law enforcement immediately.\n\n### Adjustments:\n\n- Evacuation routes near the south/southeast must be confirmed as blocked and alternate routes communicated via PA.\n- Turnstile exits from parking lots are creating bottlenecks; direct security to open emergency gates or override badge readers to allow free egress.\n- Trapped personnel reports in the Assembly building require immediate relay to incoming fire/rescue units.\n- Wind direction must be assessed immediately to determine toxic smoke plume trajectory and whether any evacuation assembly points or the command post are downwind and need relocation.\n- The potential for secondary attack must be communicated to all arriving law enforcement; no vehicles should be permitted onto the site without verification until law enforcement secures the perimeter.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2: Minutes Five Through Fifteen (12:39 PM – 12:49 PM)\n\n### Decision 7: Establish Formal Incident Command Structure and Assign Roles\n\n**Decision:** With available leadership assembled at the command center, formally activate the Incident Command Team structure with clear role assignments:\n- **Incident Commander:** Plant Manager (until external emergency services arrive and command is transferred per ICS protocols)\n- **Safety Officer:** Occupational Safety and Health Director (currently at truck entrance; safety oversight delegated to OSH staff at command post)\n- **Operations Section:** Assembly Director, BIW Director, Paint Shop Director (building-specific evacuation verification and damage assessment)\n- **Planning Section:** Engineering Director (shutdown operations, structural assessment coordination)\n- **Logistics Section:** Logistics/Shipping Director (resource coordination, supply chain notification)\n- **Finance/Administration Section:** Finance Director (emergency purchase orders, cost tracking per corporate directive that cost is no concern during true emergencies)\n- **Environmental Unit Leader:** Environmental Director (spill response, regulatory notification, air monitoring)\n- **Liaison Officer:** HR Director (law enforcement coordination, employee accountability, family notification coordination)\n- **Public Information Officer (interim):** Executive Secretary (coordinates with Corporate Media Relations Director; no public statements made from site—all public-facing communication goes through corporate)\n\n**Why:** ICS principles require clear role delegation, unity of command, and manageable span of control. With a 10-person leadership team managing a catastrophic event involving 10,300+ personnel, multiple active hazards, destroyed infrastructure, environmental contamination, and incoming multi-agency response, formal structure prevents duplication of effort, missed critical actions, and communication breakdowns. Each director's assigned role aligns with their normal functional expertise and established emergency procedures.\n\n### Decision 8: Initiate Employee Accountability Process\n\n**Decision:** Direct the HR Director to activate the badge access system to begin determining who was on-site at the time of the explosion. Cross-reference badge-in records against badge-out records at evacuation points. Begin headcount at all evacuation assembly points using shift rosters for all three categories: direct employees, contract employees, and visitors.\n\n**Why:** With approximately 3,400–3,500 personnel on the current shift, identifying who is missing is critical for directing search-and-rescue efforts. The digital badge reader system at every turnstile entrance provides a record of who entered the facility. As evacuees badge out or are counted at assembly points, the gap between known-in and accounted-for personnel identifies the missing population. This data directly informs fire/rescue prioritization when they arrive.\n\n### Decision 9: Establish On-Site Triage and Medical Staging Area\n\n**Decision:** Designate a location upwind of the fires and away from the blast zone as a medical triage and staging area. Direct any on-site personnel with medical or first-aid training to report to this location to begin initial casualty treatment. Prepare the area for incoming EMS units to use as a base for triage, treatment, and helicopter landing (if applicable).\n\n**Why:** With mass casualties and EMS units still en route through congested traffic, on-site first-response medical care is the only immediate option for injured personnel. Burns, blast injuries, and smoke inhalation require immediate basic care (airway management, bleeding control, burn cooling) to prevent preventable deaths. Centralizing casualties at a triage point also prevents injured personnel from wandering into traffic or collapsing in areas where they cannot be found. When EMS arrives, a pre-established staging area dramatically accelerates their operational setup.\n\n### Decision 10: Initiate Environmental Emergency Response\n\n**Decision:** Direct the Environmental Director to:\n1. Deploy on-site environmental spill response personnel and equipment to attempt to block or divert oil flow to storm sewers using booms, absorbents, or drain covers—only if it is safe to do so given fire proximity.\n2. Immediately call the National Response Center (NRC) to report the release of oil to international navigable waterways.\n3. Begin contacting external professional spill cleanup contractors for emergency mobilization.\n4. Initiate air monitoring downwind of the battery fire to assess toxic gas concentrations for community health risk.\n\n**Why:** Oil has already reached international navigable waterways, triggering mandatory federal reporting requirements under the Clean Water Act and the Oil Pollution Act. The NRC notification is legally required and initiates federal response coordination (Coast Guard, EPA). On-site defensive spill measures, per general employee training protocols, can slow the flow if personnel can safely access storm drain interception points. However, the scale of this spill—an entire oil/fuel storage area with oil flowing freely—will require professional external cleanup contractors. The lithium-phosphate battery fire poses an airborne toxic hazard that could affect surrounding communities, requiring air monitoring data to inform potential community shelter-in-place or evacuation decisions by local authorities.\n\n### Decision 11: Notify FBI and Department of Homeland Security\n\n**Decision:** Contact the FBI Detroit Field Office and the Department of Homeland Security to report the confirmed terrorist attack on a critical manufacturing facility.\n\n**Why:** This is a confirmed intentional attack using a vehicle-borne improvised explosive device (the fuel truck). Federal law enforcement agencies have jurisdiction over terrorism investigations and will need to secure the crime scene, investigate the attacker's identity and potential network, and assess whether additional threats exist. Early federal notification also activates national-level resources (FBI Evidence Response Teams, DHS infrastructure protection assets) and ensures coordination with local law enforcement already on scene.\n\n### Decision 12: Notify Corporate Emergency Management and Executive Leadership\n\n**Decision:** The Plant Manager personally calls corporate emergency management and executive leadership to provide an initial situation report: confirmed terrorist attack, mass casualties, multiple buildings destroyed/damaged, environmental contamination of waterways, all operations ceased, emergency services responding.\n\n**Why:** Corporate must be notified to activate enterprise-level response resources, including the business continuity team, corporate legal, corporate communications, insurance/risk management, and executive crisis management. The corporate media relations director must be alerted immediately because media will arrive at the scene within minutes and inquiries will begin almost instantly. Corporate leadership must be prepared to issue holding statements and manage information flow.\n\n### Decision 13: Notify Corporate Media Relations Director and Establish Communication Protocol\n\n**Decision:** Direct the Executive Secretary to contact the corporate media relations director immediately and establish the following communication protocol:\n- **All public-facing communications** will be managed exclusively by the corporate media relations director.\n- **No on-site personnel** are authorized to speak to media under any circumstances.\n- **Messaging timing:** An initial holding statement should be prepared by corporate communications for release within 30–60 minutes acknowledging the incident, confirming emergency response is underway, and directing the public to a designated information channel.\n- **Subsequent updates** will be issued by corporate at regular intervals as information is verified.\n- **Plant-level responsibility:** The Executive Secretary serves as the site liaison to corporate communications, funneling verified information from the Incident Commander to the corporate media relations director.\n- **Employee communication:** HR Director coordinates internal employee communications separately from public-facing messaging, using the employee cell phone database for mass text notifications once content is approved by the Incident Commander.\n\n**Why:** In a terrorist attack with mass casualties at a major automotive plant, media coverage will be immediate, intense, and global. Uncontrolled or inconsistent messaging from the site creates legal liability, exacerbates public panic, interferes with law enforcement investigation, and can cause reputational damage that compounds the crisis. The corporate media relations director is the designated professional for this function. Establishing the protocol now—before cameras arrive—prevents ad hoc communications. Employee families will be desperate for information; the HR mass notification system provides a controlled channel for verified information to reach families before they learn details from news coverage.\n\n### Decision 14: Direct Logistics Director to Halt All Inbound Shipments and Coordinate Site Access\n\n**Decision:** Direct the Logistics/Shipping Director to:\n1. Immediately halt all inbound truck and rail shipments to the facility.\n2. Coordinate with security and law enforcement to establish a controlled vehicle access point for emergency vehicles only.\n3. Begin notifying the corporate business continuity team of complete production stoppage and supply chain halt.\n4. Identify and halt all outbound vehicle shipments; no car carriers or transport trucks are to approach the site.\n\n**Why:** With 200–300 semi-trucks and dozens of rail cars arriving daily under the JIT supply chain model, inbound trucks will begin arriving at a site that is on fire, has no operating receiving docks, and has roads that must be reserved for emergency vehicles. Trucks arriving at a chaotic scene will compound traffic gridlock. Rail cars in transit must be held at origin or staging yards. The JIT model means suppliers will continue shipping within hours if not notified. The business continuity team must begin coordinating North American-wide production adjustments immediately, as this plant's shutdown will cascade through the supply network. Outbound vehicle carriers must also be halted, as the vehicle storage area may be within the affected zone and the site is an active emergency/crime scene.\n\n### Decision 15: Finance Director Activates Emergency Procurement Authority\n\n**Decision:** Direct the Finance Director to coordinate with the corporate finance team to activate unlimited emergency purchase order authority for all incident-related expenditures, including medical supplies, environmental cleanup contractors, temporary facilities, food/water for responders, and any other resources identified by the Incident Command Team.\n\n**Why:** Per established corporate policy, cost must not be a concern during true emergency events. Advance activation of emergency procurement authority ensures no delays occur when the Environmental Director needs to contract a $500,000 spill cleanup operation, when medical supplies must be purchased for triage operations, or when any other time-critical resource is needed. The Finance Director and corporate finance team handle the administrative mechanics; the Incident Commander and section chiefs can authorize expenditures without waiting for normal approval chains.\n\n---\n\n## Decision-Gate Checkpoint 2 (12:49 PM — Transition from Phase 2 to Phase 3)\n\n### Information Reassessment:\n\nAt the fifteen-minute mark, the following updated information is available:\n\n- **Evacuation status:** Approximately 70–80% of on-shift personnel have reached assembly points or exited the facility. Badge data is being compiled. Significant numbers of personnel remain unaccounted for, particularly from the Assembly building and areas near the blast zone. Building sweeps of unaffected buildings (BIW, Utilities, Administration) are being organized by building directors per closure policy.\n- **Emergency responder status:** First police units have arrived and are establishing a perimeter. Fire and EMS units are approaching but still experiencing traffic delays; police are working to clear corridors. Initial estimates suggest 5–10 minutes until first fire units arrive on scene.\n- **Fire status:** Fires are intensifying at the battery storage area. The gasoline and oil fires are burning intensely but appear contained to the immediate storage area. Toxic smoke from battery fires is drifting based on wind direction (which has been determined and communicated). No secondary explosions have occurred.\n- **Environmental status:** Oil continues flowing to storm sewers. Environmental staff have deployed limited booming at accessible drain points. NRC has been notified. External cleanup contractors have been contacted and are mobilizing with estimated arrival times of 45–90 minutes.\n- **Casualty status:** At least 15–20 injured personnel have been brought to the triage staging area with burns, lacerations, and blast injuries. At least 5–8 fatalities are visually confirmed in the blast zone, though the actual number is likely significantly higher. Ambulances have not yet arrived.\n- **Federal notification:** FBI and DHS have been contacted. FBI agents are en route.\n- **Corporate notification:** Corporate emergency management is activating enterprise-level crisis response. Corporate media relations director has been briefed and is preparing an initial public statement.\n- **Traffic/access:** Roads remain severely congested. Police are making progress on clearing emergency corridors. Employee vehicles are gridlocked in parking lots and on surrounding roads.\n- **Security assessment:** No evidence of secondary threats, but law enforcement has not yet fully secured the perimeter. The fuel truck driver is presumed deceased in the blast.\n\n### Adjustments:\n\n- Shift search-and-rescue communication priority: as fire units arrive, immediately brief them on unaccounted personnel locations (Assembly building, blast zone vicinity) and battery fire hazards (lithium-phosphate specific risks including toxic gas, thermal runaway, water-reactivity concerns).\n- Expand triage area and prepare for mass ambulance staging as EMS units begin arriving.\n- Reassess wind direction and toxic plume trajectory; if community areas are downwind of battery fire, coordinate with local emergency management for potential community notification.\n- Formalize the crime scene boundary in coordination with arriving FBI agents—balance evidence preservation with life-safety and environmental response needs.\n- Begin preparing a comprehensive situation report for the corporate crisis team, including estimated casualties, infrastructure damage, environmental impact scope, and estimated duration of complete shutdown.\n- Initiate contact with Michigan EGLE and EPA Region 5 for environmental regulatory notification.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 3: Minutes Fifteen Through Sixty (12:49 PM – 1:34 PM)\n\n### Decision 16: Transfer Incident Command to External Emergency Services Upon Arrival\n\n**Decision:** Upon arrival of the senior fire department incident commander and/or federal law enforcement on-scene commander, formally transfer incident command authority per ICS protocols. The Plant Manager and leadership team transition to a support and advisory role within the unified command structure, providing site-specific expertise, building layouts, hazardous materials information, personnel data, and operational support.\n\n**Why:** Per established ICS protocols and plant procedures, incident command transfers to external emergency responders upon their arrival. Fire, HazMat, and law enforcement professionals have the training, equipment, and authority to manage active firefighting, search and rescue in collapsed structures, hazardous materials response, and crime scene operations. Plant leadership's value shifts to providing critical institutional knowledge: building layouts, chemical inventories, personnel locations, utility shutoff confirmations, and environmental data. This transition is not an abdication of responsibility—the Plant Manager remains the highest-ranking company official on-site and retains responsibility for all company decisions, employee welfare, environmental response coordination, business continuity, and communication with corporate.\n\n### Decision 17: Complete Building Sweeps of All Non-Destroyed Buildings\n\n**Decision:** Direct the Assembly Director, BIW Director, and Paint Shop Director (for unaffected sections) to coordinate final building sweeps of all evacuated buildings per building closure policy, confirming no personnel remain inside. Report sweep completion status to the Incident Command post.\n\n**Why:** Building closure policy requires a final leadership sweep after evacuation. In a panicked evacuation, personnel may be injured, disoriented, hiding, or trapped in restrooms, offices, or enclosed spaces. The BIW building, Utilities building, and Administration building were outside the 600-ft blast radius but may have personnel who did not hear alarms, were injured by secondary effects (falling debris, shattered glass), or who have mobility limitations. Confirming all non-destroyed buildings are clear narrows the search focus to the damaged areas where fire/rescue teams are operating.\n\n### Decision 18: Expand Medical Operations and Coordinate Mass Casualty Transport\n\n**Decision:** As EMS units arrive, integrate on-site triage ope