ly suppressed with water alone and may require specialized dry chemical agents or controlled burn-down.\n\n**Why:** The environmental contamination is multi-media (air, water, and soil) and involves multiple regulated substances (petroleum products in navigable waterways, hazardous air emissions from battery combustion, potential heavy metal contamination from batteries). Federal and state regulatory agencies (EPA, EGLE, Coast Guard via NRC) require timely notification and will likely deploy their own response teams. The professional cleanup contractors bring the heavy equipment (vacuum trucks, boom systems, skimmers) necessary for a spill of this magnitude. Air monitoring data is critical for community health protection decisions. All response actions must be documented contemporaneously for regulatory compliance, legal defense, and insurance purposes.\n\n### Decision 20: Establish Incident Documentation Protocols\n\n**Decision:** Designate a member of each section (Operations, Planning, Logistics, Finance, Environmental) to serve as a dedicated documentation recorder. All decisions, actions, times, observations, and communications are to be logged in written form beginning immediately. Photographs and video documentation of damage, response actions, and conditions are to be captured systematically (coordinated with law enforcement to avoid interfering with the criminal investigation).\n\n**Why:** This incident will be the subject of multiple investigations (FBI criminal investigation, OSHA investigation, EPA investigation, state regulatory investigation, corporate investigation, insurance claims, and likely civil litigation). Contemporaneous documentation is the gold standard for legal defensibility and regulatory compliance. Time-stamped records of who made what decisions and why, what actions were taken, what was observed, and what communications occurred are essential. Delayed documentation is less reliable and less credible. The documentation burden must be distributed so that decision-makers can focus on response while dedicated recorders capture the record.\n\n### Decision 21: Coordinate with Law Enforcement on Crime Scene Management\n\n**Decision:** Work with arriving FBI agents and local law enforcement to establish crime scene boundaries that balance evidence preservation with ongoing life-safety and environmental response operations. Provide facility security camera footage, access control logs, visitor records, and truck delivery schedules to law enforcement immediately. Identify the fuel delivery company and provide all available information about the driver and the scheduled delivery.\n\n**Why:** This is a federal crime scene. Evidence preservation is important, but it cannot override life-safety (search and rescue operations) or environmental emergency response (stopping oil flow to waterways). Establishing agreed-upon boundaries and protocols with FBI early prevents conflict between response objectives. Access control data, security camera footage, and delivery records will be critical to the investigation and may reveal whether the attacker acted alone, had inside information, or was part of a larger plot. Providing this data proactively demonstrates full cooperation and may help identify any ongoing threats.\n\n### Decision 22: Initiate Business Continuity Coordination\n\n**Decision:** Direct the Logistics/Shipping Director to work with the corporate business continuity team on the following immediate actions:\n1. Formally notify all Tier 1 suppliers to halt shipments immediately.\n2. Coordinate with rail carriers to hold all cars destined for the facility.\n3. Assess the status of the approximately 6,000 finished vehicles stored on-site—determine which are in the affected zone and which can eventually be shipped.\n4. Identify alternate production capacity at other facilities in North America for the vehicle models produced at this plant.\n5. Notify the dealer network through corporate channels that vehicle 